reviews.text: I've read similar warnings from different brands, so I chose this product over the others. My device was correctly installed within safety standards and load guidelines; however, about a month after installation, this product failed at the switch, almost starting a house fire. I came home to the smell of burning plastic, a fire alarm, and my pets going wild. I discovered the switch smoking and melting just in time to prevent a fire. I could have lost my home over this substandard piece of equipment. I bought four of these and immediately removed the other devices for safety. BUYER BEWARE; DON’T TAKE THE RISK!

reviews.title: WARNING: FIRE HAZARD!

reviews.productTitle: 2Pack UL Listed Rotary Dimmer Switch with1.8m/5.9ft Extension Power Cord for Halogen and Incandescent Bulbs lamp, Compatible with LED dimmable Lights
reviews.text: I don't know why more lamps and devices don't come with an in-line slider or dial — glad to find this replacement! I took apart two lamps, spliced the cord in, and it works like a charm. Because my lamps in particular didn't disassemble down to the terminals, I used some heat-shrink tubing at the point of wires connecting. I didn't solder, but that's also an option if you worry about the lines coming apart. Two things to know: 1. The cord length is short. You basically have to have your lamp right next to an outline. And since you can't move the dimmer box up and down on the cable, it may end up in an awkward position. 2. As others have noted, the rotation isn't purely linear. Basically the first 50% of rotation has no effect, leaving all the dimming action into a relatively small range of motion. Still, it's much less bulky than the plug-in dimmers which introduce an extra 6 feet of cord all jumped in the same place.
reviews.date: Reviewed in the United States on August 15, 2020
reviews.title: A great choice for in-line dimming.

reviews.productTitle: 2Pack UL Listed Rotary Dimmer Switch with1.8m/5.9ft Extension Power Cord for Halogen and Incandescent Bulbs lamp, Compatible with LED dimmable Lights
reviews.text: I wish they had made it much clearer that one end of this dimmer switch is EXPOSED WIRE. If you're like me, and you thought you could just plug your lights into one end and plug the other end into the wall, well, you'd be wrong. After my initial shock at finding the exposed wire on one end (seriously, WHY?), I gave it my best attempt anyway and wrapped the filaments around the prongs of my lights (which seems like an extremely dangerous thing to have to do...) and plugged it in. when the dimmer switch is turned all the way up, my lights work at full strength. anywhere else and the lights have a very fast strobe/flicker effect...still at full brightness though. I bought this specifically to help with my video making setup and it's utterly useless, unless I was going for an "epilepsy warning needed" vibe. terrible product and very disappointing. will be pursuing a refund with amazon because screw this. Do not buy!
reviews.date: Reviewed in the United States on July 24, 2020
reviews.title: Not what I expected and doesn't function as a dimmer
